â­• PHP Session and Cookie

ğŸ›‘ Cookies

    âœ… A cookie is a small file with the maximum size of 4KB that the web server stores on the client computer.
    âœ… Http is a stateless protocol; cookies allow us to track the state of the application using small files stored on the userâ€™s computer.The path were the cookies are stored depends on the browser.Internet Explorer usually stores them in Temporal Internet Files folder.
    âœ… Personalizing the user experience â€“ this is achieved by allowing users to select their preferences.The page requested that follow are personalized based on the set preferences in the cookies.
    âœ… Tracking the pages visited by a user

    âœ” Creating Cookies:

    âœ… Example:

        <?php

        setcookie(cookie_name, cookie_value, [expiry_time], [cookie_path], [domain], [secure], [httponly]);

        ?>

    âœ” Retrieving Cookie Value

    âœ…

        <?php
            print_r($_COOKIE);    //output the contents of the cookie array variable 
        ?>

    âœ” Deleting cookie_name
    
    âœ…

        <?php

        setcookie("user_name", "Guru99", time() - 360,'/');

        ?>

ğŸ›‘ Session

âœ… A session is a global variable stored on the server.
âœ… Each session is assigned a unique id which is used to retrieve stored values.
âœ… Whenever a session is created, a cookie containing the unique session id is stored on the userâ€™s computer and returned with every request to the server. 
    If the client browser does not support cookies, the unique php session id is displayed in the URL
âœ… Sessions have the capacity to store relatively large data compared to cookies.
âœ… The session values are automatically deleted when the browser is closed. If you want to store the values permanently, then you should store them in the database.
âœ… Just like the $_COOKIE array variable, session variables are stored in the $_SESSION array variable. Just like cookies, the session must be started before any HTML tags.

ğŸ¤ Why and when to use Sessions?

1.You want to store important information such as the user id more securely on the server where malicious users cannot temper with them.
2.You want to pass values from one page to another.
3.You want the alternative to cookies on browsers that do not support cookies.
4.You want to store global variables in an efficient and more secure way compared to passing them in the URL
5.You are developing an application such as a shopping cart that has to temporary store information with a capacity larger than 4KB.

    âœ” Creating Session:
        
        Example:

        <?php

        session_start(); //start the PHP_session function 

        if(isset($_SESSION['page_count']))
        {
            $_SESSION['page_count'] += 1;
        }
        else
        {
            $_SESSION['page_count'] = 1;
        }
        echo 'You are visitor number ' . $_SESSION['page_count'];

        ?>
    
    âœ” Destroying Session Variables

        The session_destroy() function is used to destroy the whole Php session variables.

            Example:

                <?php

                session_destroy(); //destroy entire session 

                ?>

        If you want to destroy only a session single item, you use the unset() function.

            Example:

                <?php

                unset($_SESSION['product']); //destroy product session item 

                ?>
    
        Session_destroy removes all the session data including cookies associated with the session.

        Unset only frees the individual session variables.

        Other data remains intact.
    
â­• PHP Registration Form using GET, POST Methods 

ğŸ›‘ What is Form?

âœ… Forms are used to get input from the user and submit it to the web server for processing.

ğŸ›‘ When and why we are using forms?

âœ… Forms come in handy when developing flexible and dynamic applications that accept user input.
âœ… Forms can be used to edit already existing data from the database

ğŸ›‘ Create a form

Example:

    <html>
    <head>
        <title>Registration Form</title>
        <meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=UTF-8">
    </head>
    <body>

        <h2>Registration Form</h2>

        <form action="registration_form.php" method="POST"> First name:

            <input type="text" name="firstname"> <br> Last name:

            <input type="text" name="lastname"> 

            <input type="hidden" name="form_submitted" value="1" />

            <input type="submit" value="Submit">

        </form>
    </body>
    </html>

âœ… <input type=â€hiddenâ€ name=â€form_submittedâ€ value=â€1â€³/> is a hidden value that is used to check whether the form has been submitted or not

ğŸ›‘ Submitting the form data to the server

The action attribute of the form specifies the submission URL that processes the data. The method attribute specifies the submission type.

âœ… PHP POST method

    âœ” This is the built in PHP super global array variable that is used to get values submitted via HTTP POST method.
    âœ” The array variable can be accessed from any script in the program; it has a global scope.
    âœ” This method is ideal when you do not want to display the form post values in the URL.
    âœ” A good example of using post method is when submitting login details to the server.

    It has the following syntax.

    <?php
        $_POST['variable_name'];
    ?>
                                    HERE,
                                        â€œ$_POST[â€¦]â€ is the PHP array
                                        â€œâ€™variable_nameâ€™â€ is the URL variable name.

âœ… PHP GET method

    âœ” This is the built in PHP super global array variable that is used to get values submitted via HTTP GET method.
    âœ” The array variable can be accessed from any script in the program; it has a global scope.
    âœ” This method displays the form values in the URL.
    âœ” Itâ€™s ideal for search engine forms as it allows the users to book mark the results.
    
    It has the following syntax.

    <?php
        $_GET['variable_name'];
    ?>
                                HERE,
                                â€œ$_GET[â€¦]â€ is the PHP array
                                â€œâ€™variable_nameâ€™â€ is the URL variable name.

