â­• PHP Try Catch Example: Exception & Error Handling

ğŸ›‘ What is an Exception?

âœ… An error is an unexpected program result that cannot be handled by the program itself.

âœ… Errors are resolved by fixing the program. An example of an error would be an infinite loop that never stops executing.

âœ… An exception is unexpected program result that can be handled by the program itself.

âœ… Examples of exception include trying to open a file that does not exist.

âœ… This exception can be handled by either creating the file or presenting the user with an option of searching for the file.

ğŸ›‘ Why handle exception?

âœ… Avoid unexpected results on our pages which can be very annoying or irritating to our end users

âœ… Improve the security of our applications by not exposing information which malicious users may use to attack our applications

âœ… Php Exceptions are used to change the normal flow of a program if any predictable error occurs.

ğŸ›‘ PHP Error handling

âœ… When an error occurs, depending on your configuration settings, PHP displays the error message in the web browser with information relating to the error that occurred.

âœ… We are going to look at three (3) commonly used methods;

        Die statements â€“ the die function combines the echo and exit function in one. 
                        It is very useful when we want to output a message and stop the script execution when an error occurs.
        
        Custom error handlers â€“ these are user defined functions that are called whenever an error occurs.
        
        PHP error reporting â€“ the error message depending on your PHP error reporting settings. 
                            This method is very useful in development environment when you have no idea what caused the error. 
                            The information displayed can help you debug your application.

ğŸ›‘ Error Handling Examples

âœ… Custom error handlers are powerful in the sense that
        
        They allow us to customize the error messages.
        The custom error handler can also include error logging in a file/database, emailing the developer etc.

âœ… 
    <?php
    error_reporting($reporting_level);
    ?>
            HERE,

            â€œerror_reportingâ€ is the PHP error reporting function
            â€œ$reporting_levelâ€ is optional, can be used to set the reporting level. 
            If no reporting level has been specified, PHP will use the default error reporting level as specified in the php.ini file.

    Reporting Level	            Description	Example
    +-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+

    E_WARNING	                Displays warning messages only. Does not halt the execution of the script	error_reporting(E_WARNING);
    E_NOTICE	                Displays notices that can occur during normal execution of a program or could be an error.	error_reporting(E_ NOTICE);
    E_USER_ERROR	            Displays user generated errors i.e. custom error handler	error_reporting(E_ USER_ERROR);
    E_USER_WARNING	            Displays user generated warning messages	error_reporting(E_USER_WARNING);
    E_USER_NOTICE	            Displays user generated notices	error_reporting(E_USER_NOTICE);
    E_RECOVERABLE_ERROR	        Displays error that are not fatal and can be handled using custom error handlers	error_reporting(E_RECOVERABLE_ERROR);
    E_ALL	                    Displays all errors and warnings	error_reporting(E_ ALL);

ğŸ›‘ Difference between Errors and Exception:

âœ… Exceptions are thrown and intended to be caught while errors are generally irrecoverable.

âœ… Exceptions are handled in an object oriented way.This means when an exception is thrown; an exception object is created that contains the exception details.

ğŸ›‘ The table below shows the exception object methods

âœ… getMessage()	Displays the exceptionâ€™s message	

        <?php
        echo $e->getMessage();
        ?>

âœ… getCode()	Displays the numeric code that represents the exception	

        <?php
        echo $e->getCode();
        ?>

âœ… getFile()	Displays the file name and path where the exception occurred	

        <?php
        echo $e->getFile();
        ?>

âœ… getLine()	Displays the line number where the exception occurred	

        <?php
        echo $e->getLine();
        ?>

âœ… getTrace()	Displays an array of the backtrace before the exception	

        <?php
        print_r( $e->getTrace());
        ?>

âœ… getPrevious()	Displays the previous exception before the current one	

        <?php
        echo $e->getPrevious();
        ?>
        
âœ… getTraceAsString()	Displays the backtrace of the exception as a string instead of an array	

        <?php
        echo $e->getTraceAsString();
        ?>

âœ… __toString()	Displays the entire exception as a string	

        <?php
        echo $e->__toString();
        ?>

âœ… 
    <?php
    throw new Exception("This is an exception example");
    ?>
        HERE,

        â€œthrowâ€ is the keyword used to throw the exception
        â€œnew Exception(â€¦)â€ creates an exception object and passes â€œThis is an exception example â€œ string as the message parameter.

âœ… 

    <?php
    try {
        $var_msg = "This is an exception example";
        throw new Exception($var_msg);
    }
    catch (Exception $e) {
        echo "Message: " . $e->getMessage();
        echo "";
        echo "getCode(): " . $e->getCode();
        echo "";
        echo "__toString(): " . $e->__toString();
    }
    ?>

ğŸ›‘ Multiple Exceptions

âœ… Multiple exception use multiple try catch blocks to handle the thrown exceptions. Multiple exceptions are useful when;

        You want to display a customized message depending on the exception thrown
        You want to perform a unique operation depending on the exception thrown

